<big><big><big><big>Oh, I really want to avoid this</big></big></big></big>
<div style="background-color:#00000000; margin:1em; padding:5px 80px; border:0px solid #00000000">
A gentle breeze drifts by, weeds grow in tangled abundance, dusk has quietly arrived, and the chorus of insects gradually falls silent. The lingering glow begins to withdraw—first receding from the forest’s edge, then slipping away from the tips of branches, until it finally settles upon the low leaves on the ground. Those leaves bear the last traces of brightness, before losing their color as well, leaving behind only contours of varying depth. The air thickens with moisture, clinging between skin and fabric—weightless, yet impossible to ignore.

Within this stagnant heaviness, trees stand in chaotic density, intertwining in disordered crowding. Their tangled roots spread beneath the earth, tearing roughly through the soil and carving jagged ridges across the surface. Walking through it, no step finds stable ground; one can only humbly yield to the land’s uneven rise and fall, moving in a subdued, stumbling drift. Dead branches lie scattered underfoot, layers of decaying leaves piled thick—each snapping sound dissolving quickly into the damp stillness, leaving no echo behind.

And yet, even with no path below, one cannot help but look upward. The dense canopy overlaps and interweaves, leaving only a few narrow, funnel-like gaps through which the last remnants of daylight seep through. That once-dominant azure stretched across the sky now fades slowly, irreversibly, until it nears complete darkness. When a few fragments of starlight traverse the long distance and emerge through the atmosphere, night has truly fallen.

But this transition does not last long. In the next instant, a bizarrely tinted, sense-shattering burst of light suddenly flashes forth, tearing through what once seemed like an unbreakable reality and crashing violently against a vast, mottled, yellowed screen. The image begins to tremble—silent noise flickering between cold gray and sickly pale—until, unbelievably, it reconstructs itself into something coherent.

When the image finally stabilizes, the film begins to play.

Below, rows of vehicles sit parked in order. Loudspeakers hang from corroded metal poles or are wedged into half-open windows. Inside black plastic casings, thin membranes vibrate violently; electromagnetic signals convert into dry, brittle sound waves, forcing prerecorded dialogue and orchestral music into the air, where they linger and echo in place.

Time passes with the turning of the film reel, yet remains stalled in the mire of reality. The faint clicking of interlocking gears is sealed within the projection booth, while outside there remains only a low, drawn-out hum. It stubbornly maintains its humble, simplistic logic of operation—until no one remains to wait for it to continue. That long waiting will eventually wither into ash. Only—how long will that take?


==Beginning==
As the mechanism continues, the content on the screen becomes gradually discernible—Perfect Blue, released around 1997. Its presence here is likely because this place is unlike indoor cinemas in cities, which cycle only the newest and most popular works. And so, it is casually cast upon these rows of metal shells; though it was never truly obscure, here it is reduced to little more than an ornamental opening.

Sound spills from the speakers, dry and thin. Dialogue breaks apart, emotions compressed; characters continue to run, argue, fantasize, and fall, one disordered scene following another. Yet the act of playing has lost its original meaning—it feels more like a forced attempt to sustain a surface-level continuity, barely holding together the connection between past and present.

There is something almost laughable about this—like frantically waving one’s arms in thick fog, trying to grasp fragments of shattered clouds to prove that clear skies once existed. But such effort is unnecessary; indifference would suffice. Consuming what has already passed can never bring it back—it is nothing more than residual imagery. When the environment has already changed and one cannot adapt, perhaps that consequence is the true source of fear.

And yet, perhaps this very line of thinking is mistaken. Perhaps one should seek to understand rather than blindly condemn; otherwise, such denial becomes nothing more than ignorance and folly. But then the question remains—where does the logic lie? If one remains fixated on outdated perspectives, staring at things long out of step with the present, it offers no meaning to life—only the risk of losing one’s footing entirely.

But then—who is here?


==Intermission==
In that wordless interval, I step out of the vehicle that never truly belonged to me. Nothing here seems to have an owner; everything is coated in dust. The space feels hollow, devoid of interest—so much so that only by leaving one’s place and moving slightly can one barely grasp something resembling sensation, rather than merely passing time.

Yet the vastness itself makes direction impossible. In this intermission, I cannot find a point upon which to anchor my will.

Perhaps I should surrender to bodily hunger—at least the fullness of the stomach can weave an illusion of safety. But such comfort lies far away. The vehicles along the way are arranged like a sequence, cold and unmoving, resembling pale, phosphorescent metal coffins under the dim moonlight. In the distance, countless phototactic insects beat their wings in frenzy, rushing without hesitation toward the same illusory end. I choose to turn away from that collective madness.

Avoiding the moths about to be obliterated under the harsh glow of the screen, I turn and descend into a deeper edge of darkness. In the corridors of imagination, this place once held sweet aromas and colorful confections; now, only a solitary, lifeless popcorn machine remains—like a forgotten altar, frozen in filth.

I try to press the switch. My fingertips meet only dry, rigid silence—unsurprisingly, the world does not respond. A few pale worms writhe in the leftover soil beside the base, slow yet utterly natural as they burrow into the earth. Compared to them, this hollow shell of mine, wandering the wasteland, does not even possess a patch of scorched ground in which to bury itself...?

What have I gained from this?


